    </did>
    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>Hiram Williams (1917-2003) was an American painter and art educator, known for his abstract figures and portrait work.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The 
        
        <emph render="bold">Hiram Williams Papers</emph> comprises biographical material, 
		correspondence, artwork, writings and memorabilia of the American painter and educator.  
		Focusing on the 1950s and 1960s, the collection -- which is occasionally interspersed with 
		annotations supplied by Williams -- illuminates his artistic career and, to a lesser extent, 
		his personal life.</p>
      <p>
        <emph render="bold">Correspondence-subject files</emph> (Box 1) consists of incoming letter and outgoing carbons, as 
		well as other material pertaining to art, from 1960 through 1966.  Correspondence includes 
		that of artists (Luis Eades, Hobson Pittman, William Stephens), patron Mildred Hawn, art 
		galleries and museums (Atelier Chapman Kelley, Beaumont Art Museum, Carlin Galleries, Cushman 
		Galleries, Museum of Modern Art, and others), the John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation, and 
		publisher Prentice-Hall.</p>
      <p>
        <emph render="bold">Artwork</emph> (Box 2) encompasses original book illustrations for Williams' 
        
        <emph render="italic">Notes for a Young 
		Painter</emph>, an original painting of his parents, and numerous reproductions of his work, including photographs and negatives of several exhibitions, a mural and paintings.  
		</p>
      <p>An original handwritten manuscript of an unpublished novel and miscellaneous statements on art 
		constitute 
        
        <emph render="bold">Writings</emph>.</p>
      <p>
        <emph render="bold">Memorabilia</emph> (Boxes 3 and 4) comprises family mementos, financial and legal material, lists of 
		Williams' paintings (some with prices), photographs, printed material, and teaching-related 
		items.  Family memorabilia includes Williams' baby book, his father's diary from 1938, two 
		newspaper clippings about his parents, and incoming correspondence from his mother.  Financial and 
		legal material consists of miscellaneous contracts, receipts and bank statements.  Among the 
		Photographs are some of Williams teaching at the University of Florida and miscellaneous pictures 
		of the artist, his family and friends.  Printed material contains articles, reviews, newspaper 
		clippings, and exhibition catalogs and invitations.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
      <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
      <p>Correspondence-subject files are arranged alphabetically by correspondence.  Artwork, Writings and Memorabilia are each arranged alphabetically by type of material.</p>
    </arrangement>
